# Project Report
# Customer Relationship Management (CRM) System
## Using Agile Methodology

---

**Project Name:** Customer Relationship Management System  
**Prepared By:** Junior Developer  
**Date:** January 15, 2026  
**Methodology:** Agile (Scrum)  

---

## 1. Executive Summary

The Customer Relationship Management (CRM) system is designed to help businesses manage customer interactions, sales processes, and customer data efficiently. This project is developed using Agile methodology to ensure iterative development and continuous customer feedback.

**Project Duration:** 12 weeks  
**Team Size:** 5 members  
**Budget:** Rs. 15,00,000  

---

## 2. Project Objectives

- Develop a web-based CRM system for managing customer data
- Implement sales pipeline management features
- Enable email integration for customer communication
- Provide reporting and analytics dashboards
- Ensure data security and user access control

---

## 3. Agile Methodology Overview

### 3.1 Scrum Framework

The project follows Scrum framework with following structure:
- Sprint Duration: 2 weeks
- Total Sprints: 6
- Daily Standup: 15 minutes every morning
- Sprint Planning: 4 hours at start of each sprint
- Sprint Review: 2 hours at end of each sprint
- Sprint Retrospective: 1 hour after sprint review

### 3.2 Team Roles

- Product Owner: 1
- Scrum Master: 1
- Development Team: 3
  - Frontend Developer: 1
  - Backend Developer: 1
  - Full Stack Developer: 1

---

## 4. Sprint Planning

### Sprint 1 (Week 1-2): Foundation
**Goals:**
- Setup development environment
- Design database schema
- Create user authentication module
- Implement login/logout functionality

**User Stories:**
1. As a user, I want to register an account
2. As a user, I want to login to the system
3. As a user, I want to logout from the system
4. As an admin, I want to manage user roles

**Deliverables:**
- User registration and login module
- Database setup
- Basic UI framework

### Sprint 2 (Week 3-4): Customer Management
**Goals:**
- Implement customer CRUD operations
- Add customer search functionality
- Create customer profile pages

**User Stories:**
1. As a sales person, I want to add new customers
2. As a sales person, I want to view customer details
3. As a sales person, I want to update customer information
4. As a sales person, I want to search customers

**Deliverables:**
- Customer management module
- Search functionality
- Customer detail pages

### Sprint 3 (Week 5-6): Sales Pipeline
**Goals:**
- Implement deal/opportunity management
- Create sales pipeline visualization
- Add deal tracking features

**User Stories:**
1. As a sales person, I want to create new deals
2. As a sales person, I want to track deal stages
3. As a sales manager, I want to view sales pipeline
4. As a sales person, I want to update deal status

**Deliverables:**
- Deal management module
- Pipeline dashboard
- Deal status tracking

### Sprint 4 (Week 7-8): Communication
**Goals:**
- Implement email integration
- Add activity logging
- Create notification system

**User Stories:**
1. As a user, I want to send emails to customers
2. As a user, I want to log customer interactions
3. As a user, I want to receive notifications
4. As a user, I want to view communication history

**Deliverables:**
- Email integration module
- Activity log system
- Notification feature

### Sprint 5 (Week 9-10): Reporting
**Goals:**
- Create sales reports
- Implement analytics dashboard
- Add export functionality

**User Stories:**
1. As a manager, I want to view sales reports
2. As a manager, I want to see analytics dashboard
3. As a user, I want to export reports to PDF
4. As a manager, I want to filter reports by date

**Deliverables:**
- Reporting module
- Analytics dashboard
- Export functionality

### Sprint 6 (Week 11-12): Testing & Deployment
**Goals:**
- Perform end-to-end testing
- Fix bugs and issues
- Deploy to production
- User training

**User Stories:**
1. As a tester, I want all features to work correctly
2. As a user, I want the system to be fast and responsive
3. As an admin, I want to deploy the system
4. As a user, I want training on the system

**Deliverables:**
- Tested and bug-free application
- Production deployment
- User documentation
- Training materials

---

## 5. Technology Stack

**Frontend:**
- HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript
- React.js
- Bootstrap

**Backend:**
- Java Spring Boot
- RESTful APIs
- MySQL Database

**Tools:**
- Git for version control
- JIRA for project management
- Jenkins for CI/CD
- Postman for API testing

---

## 6. Product Backlog

Priority-wise list of features:

**High Priority:**
1. User authentication
2. Customer management
3. Deal/opportunity management
4. Search functionality

**Medium Priority:**
5. Email integration
6. Activity logging
7. Sales reports
8. Dashboard

**Low Priority:**
9. Notifications
10. Advanced analytics
11. Mobile app
12. Third-party integrations

---

## 7. Definition of Done

A user story is considered done when:
- Code is written and reviewed
- Unit tests are written and passing
- Integration tests are passing
- Feature is deployed to staging
- Product owner has accepted the feature
- Documentation is updated

---

## 8. Risk Management

**Identified Risks:**

1. Team member unavailability
   - Mitigation: Cross-training team members

2. Technology challenges
   - Mitigation: Proof of concept in early sprints

3. Scope creep
   - Mitigation: Strict backlog prioritization

4. Integration issues
   - Mitigation: Early integration testing

---

## 9. Metrics and KPIs

**Velocity:** Average story points completed per sprint  
**Burn-down Chart:** Track remaining work in sprint  
**Bug Rate:** Number of bugs per sprint  
**Code Coverage:** Minimum 80% test coverage  
**Customer Satisfaction:** Feedback score from product owner  

---

## 10. Testing Strategy

**Types of Testing:**
- Unit Testing (JUnit)
- Integration Testing
- Functional Testing
- User Acceptance Testing
- Performance Testing
- Security Testing

**Testing Approach:**
- Test-Driven Development (TDD)
- Continuous Integration
- Automated regression testing

---

## 11. Deployment Strategy

**Environments:**
- Development
- Staging
- Production

**Deployment Process:**
1. Code commit to Git
2. Automated build in Jenkins
3. Run automated tests
4. Deploy to staging
5. UAT in staging
6. Deploy to production

---

## 12. Conclusion

The CRM project using Agile methodology allows for:
- Iterative development
- Regular customer feedback
- Flexibility to change requirements
- Early delivery of working software
- Better risk management
- Improved team collaboration

**Expected Outcomes:**
- Fully functional CRM system
- High customer satisfaction
- Maintainable codebase
- Well-documented system
- Trained users

---

## 13. Appendix

**Sprint Retrospective Notes:**
- What went well
- What needs improvement
- Action items for next sprint

**Lessons Learned:**
- Early user involvement is crucial
- Regular communication prevents misunderstandings
- Automated testing saves time
- Small incremental changes are better than big bang releases
